			<span class="anthracite size13" contentbodystyle="Anthracite">Hi Chief!  Good story.  I partially agree with Eric's idea of contacting the IT department at the husband's company.  But for a different reason.  I'd let them know something is going on.  With all the reported chat's going on, the husband may just be having some extramarital adventures.  On the company dime.  And on the company's legal liability, with an annoyed and potentially litiguous wife in the wings.  However, the thought occurred that he might also be running a side business on company assets and on company time.  Either could get the head of their IT department interested enough to cut his access outside of normal working hours.  I would try to get an inside investigation going, that didn't include me particularly, and try to force him off the company network and away from Citrix.  The husband doesn't sound like he is particularly adept at working with computers, although I could be wrong.  He might just be extremely lazy.  The idea of forcing him away from the company network / Citrix is to "encourage" him to use something available that is "easy" and insecure (cough _aol__ cough cough excuse me, bad cold).  If I can get him away from the citrix network and onto either a lame national dial-up, or cable, then I don't really have to worry about third parties anymore.  And if _I_ am not involved in him leaving the land of Citrix, so much the better!  Once he's off Citrix, there are any number of things which could be done, and you've already been through most of them.  One other thing that could be considered once the husband is off the Citrix net, since you already have the wife's legal permission to check out that machine, is to configure a VLAN going out some out of the way port to a box of your choice.  In a safe dog and husband free environment.  Save you some grief checking the files.  </span>
		</div>
           
